<span class="displaytext"><b> <u>governor (candidate last) discusses governor (candidate full)'s playground diplomacy in humboldt, iowa (12/14/07):</u> </b> <p><b>governor (candidate full):</b> "you also heard my comments, my remarks today, about governor (candidate last)'s article in <em>foreign affairs</em>. to accuse the president of an arrogant, bunker mentality is, in my view, more fitting from a person running from the (PARTY NAME) party than from our own. it sounds like something (candidate full) or (candidate full) would say. not what you'd hear from someone running for president as a (PARTY NAME). and i think it was a very serious error. with that, i'd be happy to take any questions you may have." </p><p><b>reporter:</b> "yesterday, you said you weren't going to compare your foreign policy experience with governor (candidate last)'s. in light of this article that has come out now, does that show a lack of judgment on his part in terms of foreign affairs? </p><p><b>governor (candidate last):</b> "well, having looked at the article, i must admit some things were also surprising. his suggestion that foreign affairs was like a children's playground is not exactly the allegory i would draw in mind. it's a far more serious and complicated and monumental effort than kids in school, but i'm sure i'll have more thoughts about his article. but i was disappointed in the quality of the thinking and the quality of recommendations there. but that which really stood out, of course, was the accusation that the administration, the accusation of the president's administration as being arrogant, bunker mentality, an administration that had been counterproductive both here and abroad. we've been safe here. how can one possibly say that when we have been safe in this country and we took action abroad at a time when the taliban had made afghanistan a safe haven for terror, libya was developing nuclear technology and iraq was a partner in efforts of terror." </p><p>... </p><p><b>reporter:</b> "governor (candidate last), just a few minutes ago you called governor (candidate last) a great friend. did it surprise you the foreign affairs article that came out today?" </p><p><b>governor (candidate last):</b> "it did surprise me. his comments surprised me. they disappointed me. i expected a great deal more from the article than i saw, but the attack on the presidency was something uncalled for. it was unnecessary and inaccurate." (governor (candidate full), media availability, humboldt, ia, 12/15/07) </p><p><b> <u>read the <em>foreign affairs</em> articles: <br/></u> </b> <br/> <b>- governor (candidate full), " rising to a new generation of global challenges," <em> <a href="http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20070701faessay86402/mitt-(candidate last)/rising-to-a-new-generation-of-global-challenges.html">foreign affairs</a> </em> , july/august 2007</b> <br/> <b>- governor michael d. (candidate last), "america's priorities in the war on terror," <em> <a href="http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20080101faessay87112/michael-d-(candidate last)/america-s-priorities-in-the-war-on-terror.html">foreign affairs</a> </em> , january/february 2008</b> </p><p><b> <u>if you would like to read more about governor (candidate last)'s playground diplomacy, please see:</u> </b> </p><p><b>- <a href="http://(candidate full).com/news/press-releases/no_laughing_matter_12.15">playground diplomacy</a></b> <br/> <b>- senator (candidate full), "security and opportunity for the twenty-first century," <em> <a href="http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20071101faessay86601/hillary-rodham-(candidate last)/security-and-opportunity-for-the-twenty-first-century.html">foreign affairs</a> </em> , november/december 2007<br/></b> <b>- senator (candidate full), "reengaging with the world," <em> <a href="http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20070901faessay86502/john-(candidate last)/reengaging-with-the-world.html">foreign affairs</a> </em> , september/october 2007</b> <br/> <b>- senator (candidate full), "renewing american leadership," <em> <a href="http://www.foreignaffairs.org/20070701faessay86401/barack-(candidate last)/renewing-american-leadership.html">foreign affairs</a> </em> , july/august 2007</b></p></span>



